            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the NWT tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator estimates your
                <strong
                  >Northwest Territories (NWT) territorial income tax</strong
                >
                for the 2024 tax year. It applies progressive NWT tax brackets
                to your taxable income and optionally adds an estimate of
                <strong>federal income tax</strong> so you can see your combined
                tax burden.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Calculate NWT taxable income</h3>
              <p>
                We start from your total taxable income and subtract deductions:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Taxable income (NWT)</strong> = Employment &amp; other
                  taxable income − Deductions
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>Examples of deductions:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Registered Retirement Savings Plan (RRSP) contributions</li>
                <li>Union and professional dues</li>
                <li>
                  Child care expenses and other allowable deductions on your
                  federal return
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Apply NWT tax brackets</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator uses a set of
                <strong>progressive tax brackets</strong>. Each portion of your
                income is taxed at the rate for that bracket, not all at once.
              </p>
              <p>In simplified form:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>NWT tax payable</strong> = Σ (Taxable income in
                  bracket × NWT rate for that bracket) − Non‑refundable credits
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Non‑refundable credits (NWT portion) reduce your NWT tax payable
                but cannot create a refund on their own. The most common is the
                <strong>basic personal amount</strong>, which shelters a base
                level of income from NWT tax.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Estimate federal income tax (optional)</h3>
              <p>
                If you check “Also estimate federal income tax”, the calculator
                applies a standard set of
                <strong>federal tax brackets</strong> to the same taxable
                income. This gives you:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Federal tax payable</strong></li>
                <li><strong>Total tax</strong> = NWT tax + federal tax</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Average total tax rate</strong> = Total tax ÷ taxable
                  income
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Marginal combined rate</strong> = NWT marginal rate +
                  federal marginal rate
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>4. Average vs. marginal tax rate</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Average tax rate</strong> is your total tax divided by
                  your taxable income. It answers: “What percentage of my income
                  goes to tax overall?”
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Marginal tax rate</strong> is the rate applied to your
                  <em>next</em> dollar of income. It’s key for decisions like
                  overtime, bonuses, or RRSP contributions.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Using the NWT tax calculator for planning</h2>
              <h3>RRSP and deduction planning</h3>
              <p>
                Try adjusting the <strong>Deductions</strong> field to see how
                RRSP contributions or other deductions change:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>NWT tax payable</li>
                <li>Federal tax (if enabled)</li>
                <li>Average and marginal tax rates</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Generally, the higher your marginal rate, the more valuable each
                dollar of RRSP contribution becomes in tax savings.
              </p>

              <h3>Checking your paycheque and withholdings</h3>
              <p>
                You can compare the calculator’s annual estimates with the tax
                withheld on your pay stubs:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Annualize your income (hourly × hours per week × 52, or use
                  your salary).
                </li>
                <li>Enter your expected deductions and credits.</li>
                <li>
                  Compare the estimated annual tax with the total tax withheld
                  by your employer.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Limitations and important notes</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This tool focuses on <strong>personal income tax</strong> for
                  NWT residents and does not cover corporate net worth or wealth
                  taxes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does not handle every special credit, surtax, or benefit
                  (e.g., GST/HST credit, Canada Child Benefit).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Actual tax rules and bracket thresholds are set by the
                  <strong>Government of the Northwest Territories</strong> and
                  the <strong>Canada Revenue Agency (CRA)</strong> and may
                  change.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                <strong
                  >Always refer to official CRA and NWT Finance guidance or
                  consult a qualified tax professional for filing your
                  return.</strong
                >
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about NWT tax</h2>

              <h3>Is there a separate NWT wealth or net worth tax?</h3>
              <p>
                No. The Northwest Territories does <strong>not</strong> levy a
                separate wealth or net worth tax on individuals. This calculator
                deals with <strong>income tax</strong> only, not taxes on your
                total assets.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Do NWT residents pay both federal and territorial income tax?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Yes. If you are resident in the Northwest Territories for tax
                purposes, you pay:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Federal income tax</strong> to the Government of
                  Canada, and
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Territorial income tax</strong> to the Government of
                  the Northwest Territories.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator can show both layers so you can see your combined
                tax burden.
              </p>

              <h3>Which income should I enter?</h3>
              <p>
                Enter your <strong>total taxable income</strong> before
                deductions, including salary, wages, self‑employment income,
                taxable benefits, and other income that appears on your federal
                return. Non‑taxable amounts (like certain benefits) should not
                be included.
              </p>

              <h3>Are the results exact?</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator provides a
                <strong>good‑faith estimate</strong> based on typical NWT and
                federal tax structures. However, your actual tax may differ due
                to:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Specific credits and deductions you claim</li>
                <li>Special income types (capital gains, dividends, etc.)</li>
                <li>Changes in tax law or bracket thresholds</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Where can I find official NWT tax information?</h3>
              <p>For the most accurate and up‑to‑date information, consult:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The <strong>Canada Revenue Agency (CRA)</strong> for federal
                  rules and forms
                </li>
                <li>
                  The
                  <strong
                    >Government of the Northwest Territories – Department of
                    Finance</strong
                  >
                  for territorial tax rates and credits
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>
